		<item>
		<title>The Bag</title>
		<link>http://www.brandyborges.com/?p=634</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 08 Oct 2015 16:15:38 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Brandyoldfashion]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Family Dynamic]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Cede]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Family]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.brandyborges.com/?p=634</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Someone recently commented to me that they heard Cede describe our last moments condensed down to me throwing a bag at him. I wonder why he fixates on a bag? I had just spent hours in the kitchen, sitting with him, crying and begging him not to leave. When there was nothing left to say <a class="more-link" href="http://www.brandyborges.com/?p=634">Continue reading <i class="fa fa-chevron-right"></i></a>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Someone recently commented to me that they heard Cede describe our last moments condensed down to me throwing a bag at him. I wonder why he fixates on a bag? I had just spent hours in the kitchen, sitting with him, crying and begging him not to leave. When there was nothing left to say and he assured me that NO MATTER what I DID or SAID would change his mind, I softly recoiled. I remember going downstairs to see what the boys were doing. My face was still full of tears and I could feel that my cheeks were warm. After a few minutes, I came upstairs to see what Cede was doing. He had all his clothes pulled out of the drawers where I had neatly put them, and they were in stacks on our bed. He had one bag that he was putting clothes into, but there were many more clothes. I was broken. I was defeated. I didn&#8217;t know what to do. I sat down on the edge of the bed to see if he would look me in my eyes one more time, but he was focused on packing.<span id="more-634"></span> When he fit all that he could in the bag, he had he paused. Thinking that I would be kind, that I would show him that even in the midst of our lives falling apart, I still loved him. I went to our closet and emptied out a bag that I had bought to hold all my yard for crocheting. I had bought it just a few weeks ago at Salvation Army. I pulled the bag out of the closet. &#8220;Here, you can use this.&#8221; I said with such a soft voice, I wondered if he heard my words at all. He took it from my hands and started shoving the rest of his clothes in it. The fact that he didn&#8217;t stop packing broke whatever pieces of my heart that were still left. I couldn&#8217;t stop crying as I walked through the kitchen and quickly went downstairs. One and Two were playing on their computers as if nothing was going on. Three saw my face and went upstairs. After I heard the back door shut, I went upstairs to see if he really left. Three was laying on his bed sobbing. I crawled onto his bed with him and tried not to cry myself. That moment was the beginning of the last 2 and 1/2 years of the 4 of us living without him.</p>
<p>But why is he so concerned about a bag? If I had NOT given him that bag, I&#8217;m sure he would have grabbed something else to put his clothes in. Why is my last moment of kindness towards him remembered that I threw a bag at him? I wasn&#8217;t mad. I wasn&#8217;t yelling. I was crushed, defeated, somber and numb. And even IF I had thrown the bag at him, or shoved it at him or tossed &#8211; why does a bag matter? He had already decided that he WAS NOT staying&#8230;. I had just spent hours begging him not to go. If there was any possible thing that I could have done, I would have done ANYTHING. If there was anything to say that could change his mind, believe me, I said it. Why is he so bothered by a bag?<br />
I guess I have my memories that are stuck into my brain, but the one that is the most vivid, is that he packed all his sports things and not ONE memento or picture of his 3 children. At that moment, I knew what his priorities were. And those priorities have continued to be evident in the time he&#8217;s been gone. I feel my children grasping onto anything that he&#8217;s willing to give, but after such a long time and no effort on his part, they are calmly settling into a new life&#8230;. a new life completely without him.</p>
<p><a class="a2a_button_facebook" href="http://www.addtoany.com/add_to/facebook?linkurl=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.brandyborges.com%2F%3Fp%3D634&amp;linkname=The%20Bag" title="Facebook" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"></a><a class="a2a_button_twitter" href="http://www.addtoany.com/add_to/twitter?linkurl=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.brandyborges.com%2F%3Fp%3D634&amp;linkname=The%20Bag" title="Twitter" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"></a><a class="a2a_button_google_plus" href="http://www.addtoany.com/add_to/google_plus?linkurl=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.brandyborges.com%2F%3Fp%3D634&amp;linkname=The%20Bag" title="Google+" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"></a><a class="a2a_button_pinterest" href="http://www.addtoany.com/add_to/pinterest?linkurl=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.brandyborges.com%2F%3Fp%3D634&amp;linkname=The%20Bag" title="Pinterest" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"></a><a class="a2a_dd a2a_target addtoany_share_save" href="https://www.addtoany.com/share#url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.brandyborges.com%2F%3Fp%3D634&amp;title=The%20Bag" id="wpa2a_20"></a></p>]]></content:encoded>
